 September 2014 | url-status =dead | archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20141012185734/http://www.parcbench.com/2014/06/08/the-summer-of-2014s-first-must-have-music-morgan-james-hunter/ | archivedate =12 October 2014 }}</ref><ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> On March 31, 2017, James began her multi-city \"Reckless Abandon Tour\" in support of her second studio album, ''Reckless Abandon'', released on April 7, 2017.\n\nJames is also well known for her numerous musical collaborations with the Jazz collective [[Postmodern Jukebox]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nJames was born '''Morgan Grunerud'''<ref name=\"ModBee01\">{{cite news | last =Millegan Renner | first =Lisa| title =Johansen High grad enjoying kooky, spooky role in Broadway show | newspaper =[[The Modesto Bee]]| publisher = | date =10 May 2010 | url =http://www.modbee.com/2010/05/10/1160838/johansen-high-grad-enjoying-kooky.html | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> in [[Boise, Idaho]],<ref name=\"Playbill02\">{{cite news | last =Gans | first =Andrew | title =DIVA TALK: Chatting With Godspell Star Morgan James   | newspaper =| publisher = [[Playbill]]| date =10 February 2012 | url =http://www.playbill.com/news/article/diva-talk-chatting-with-godspell-star-morgan-james-187331 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> the daughter of educators and actors Allen Grunerud and Shellie Harwood.<ref name=\"ModBee01\"/> The family moved frequently when James was a child, going from [[Pocatello, Idaho]] to [[Utah]], [[Tennessee]], and eventually [[Modesto, California|Modesto]], [[California]] where she spent her high school years.<ref name=\"HuffPost\">{{cite news|last=Bialas|first=Michael|title=First Listen: With Reckless Abandon, Morgan James Bares Her Soul Power|newspaper=[[The Huffington Post]]|publisher=The Huffington Post|date=4 April 2017|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/first-listen-with-reckless-abandon-morgan-james-bares_us_58e30fc8e4b09deecf0e19a2|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref> She has a younger brother, Nicholas, who is an avant-garde musician and comedian.<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/> James was inspired by her actor parents to enter the performing arts, and she joined a choir while in [[middle school]]. Her grandmother also bought her a karaoke machine and agreed to pay for singing lessons until James went to college.<ref name=\"Playbill02\"/>\n\nJames attended high school at [[Peter Johansen High School]] in Modesto<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/> and graduated in 1999. At the age of 14, James realized it was her dream to  attend [[The Juilliard School]] in [[New York City]], and after auditioning, she was eventually wait-listed and then rejected. However, after significant correspondence with the head of admissions, she convinced him to accept her as the class's seventh singer, one above the usual six.<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/> There, she studied [[opera]],<ref name=\"ModBee02\">{{cite news | last =Rowland | first =Marijke | title =Modesto\u2019s Morgan James \u2018on fire,\u2019 joins cabaret | newspaper =[[The Modesto Bee]]| publisher = | date =3 April 2014 | url =http://www.modbee.com/2014/04/03/3272776/modestos-morgan-james-on-fire.html | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> and eventually earned her [[Bachelor of Music]] in Voice in 2003.<ref name=\"JuilliardJournal\">{{cite news | last =Hodges | first =Bruce | title =James and Dinnerstein Release New Song CDs  | newspaper =| publisher = The Juilliard Journal| date =May 2013 | url =http://www.juilliard.edu/journal/1305/james-and-dinnerstein-release-new-song-cds?destination=node/27406 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> In college, James also took a master class headed by Broadway veteran [[Barbara Cook]].<ref name=\"Playbill02\"/>\n\n==Career==\nAfter college, James initially struggled to find work and looked for jobs that utilized both her operatic and classical training.<ref name=\"Playbill02\"/> James did not make her Broadway debut until 2010 in the musical production of ''[[The Addams Family (musical)|The Addams Family]]'', starring [[Nathan Lane]] and [[Bebe Neuwirth]].<ref name=\"ModBee01\"/> In 2011, James appeared in [[Frank Wildhorn]]'s ''Wonderland''<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\">{{cite news | title =WONDERLAND's Morgan James Plays Concert at Birdland 5/9  | newspaper =| publisher = Broadway World| date =9 May 2011 | url =http://www.broadwayworld.com/cabaret/article/WONDERLANDs-Morgan-James-Plays-Concert-at-Birdland-59-20110508 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> and the Broadway revival of ''[[Godspell]]''. James sprained her ankle in a rehearsal for ''Godspell'' in October 2011 and was unable to perform during previews.<ref name=\"Sidelined\">{{cite news | last =Gans | first =Andrew | title =Morgan James Temporarily Sidelined from Godspell; Free Concert Set for Oct. 17   | newspaper =| publisher = [[Playbill]]| date =14 October 2011 | url =http://www.playbill.com/news/article/morgan-james-temporarily-sidelined-from-godspell-free-concert-set-for-oct.--183617 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> She recuperated and, by November 2011, was performing in the musical at the [[Circle in the Square Theatre]].<ref name=\"Blank\">{{cite news | last =Blank | first =Matt | title =PHOTO EXCLUSIVE: A Three-Show Day With Godspell's Morgan James | newspaper =| publisher = [[Playbill]]| date =13 December 2011 | url =http://www.playbill.com/news/article/photo-exclusive-a-three-show-day-with-godspells-morgan-james-185513 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> In 2013, James took on the role of [[Teena Marie]] in ''[[Motown: The Musical]]''. She stayed with the cast until December 2013, when she left to pursue a vocal performance tour.<ref name=\"54Below\"/><ref name=\"ModBee02\"/>\n\nWhile on Broadway she moonlighted as a solo artist, with a backing band often composed of Chris Fenwick, Matt Fieldes, Damien Bassman, among others.<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\"/><ref name=\"Poisson\">{{cite news | last =Gans | first =Andrew | title =Addams Family's James to Offer Solo Concert In November  | newspaper =| publisher = [[Playbill]]| date =21 October 2010 | url =http://www.playbill.com/news/article/addams-familys-james-to-offer-solo-concert-in-november-172879 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> She has played at numerous New York City clubs, including [[(Le) Poisson Rouge]],<ref name=\"Poisson\"/> [[54 Below]],<ref name=\"54Below\"/> [[Rockwood Music Hall]],<ref name=\"Sidelined\"/>  and [[Birdland (jazz club)|Birdland]].<ref name=\"BroadwayWorld\"/> Her first solo album, ''Morgan James Live: A Celebration of [[Nina Simone]]'', was recorded at New York jazz club, Dizzy's, and is a collection of Nina Simone cover songs. It was released via Epic Records in December 2012.<ref name=\"AllMusic02\">{{cite news | last =Collar | first =Matt | title =Review by Matt Collar | newspaper =| publisher = [[AllMusic]]| date =4 December 2012 | url =http://www.allmusic.com/album/morgan-james-live-from-dizzys-club-coca-cola-mw0002443026 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHer second solo album (and first studio album), ''Hunter'', was recorded in 2014 and released via Epic Records in June 2014. The 11-track album was produced by [[Doug Wamble]] and is James' first album of all solo material.<ref name=\"Parcbench\"/><ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite news | last =Collar | first =Matt | title =Review by Matt Collar | newspaper =| publisher = [[AllMusic]]| date =3 June 2014 | url =http://www.allmusic.com/album/hunter-mw0002662522 | accessdate =22 September 2014}}</ref> The album included her cover of [[Prince (musician)|Prince]]'s song \"[[Call My Name (Prince song)|Call My Name]]\", which Prince allowed her to put on the record.<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/>\n\nOn December 16, 2016, James released her second cover album, ''Blue'', released on the 45th anniversary of [[Joni Mitchell]]'s album [[Blue (Joni Mitchell album)|of the same name]].<ref name=\"SoulBounce\">{{cite news|last=Cakes|first=B.|title=Morgan James Pays Homage To Joni Mitchell\u2019s \u2018Blue\u2019 & Preps For Upcoming \u2018Reckless Abandon Tour\u2019|publisher=SoulBounce|date=9 January 2017|url=http://www.soulbounce.com/soul/2017/01/morgan-james-pays-homage-to-joni-mitchells-blue-preps-for-upcoming-reckless-abandon-tour/|accessdate=4 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Reckless Abandon,'' her second solo studio album, was independently released on April 7, 2017 via her self-created Hedonist Records. It is her first album to feature completely original material and heavily incorporates elements of [[Soul music|soul]] and [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]]. On March 31, 2017, she embarked on a national headlining spring \"Reckless Abandon Tour\" in support of the album.<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/>\n\nSince 2014, James collaborates with [[Postmodern Jukebox]], producing several cover songs on their YouTube channel<ref>{{cite web|title=Postmodern Jukebox's Youtube channel|url=https://www.youtube.com/user/ScottBradleeLovesYa/search?query=Morgan+James|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref> and joining them on tour.<ref>{{cite web|title=New videos and updates|url=http://www.morganjamesonline.com/news/new-videos-and-updates/|website=morganjamesonline.com|accessdate=24 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Morgan James released The White Album, her own interpretation of The Beatles' album, on the occasion of its 50th anniversary.\n\n==Personal life==\nJames currently lives in [[Harlem]] with her husband, guitarist and producer [[Doug Wamble]], whom she wed in spring of 2016.<ref name=\"HuffPost\"/><ref name=\"SoulBounce\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"1\" | Album details\n|- \n! scope=\"row\" | ''Hunter''\n|\n*Released: November 4, 2014 <span style=\"font-size:85%;\">(US)</span><ref name=\"AllMusic\"/>\n*Label: [[Epic Records|Epic]] \n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Reckless Abandon''\n|\n*Released: April 7, 2017 <span style=\"font-size:8